nd big, and historic instead. Perhaps it would be best if Japan did a little less to please Americans on the issue of bases and host nation military support--provided that it do more in another way. Providing substantial numbers of Japanese peacekeeping troops for Sudan and Congo, as part of the ongoing U.N. missions in those places, comes to mind as a good example of possible contributions consistent with Japanese political sensibilities and with the proper role of a great power on the world stage. Moving toward a true alliance in this way could do much to not only ease the pain over an Okinawa base disagreement, but transcend it as well, and get what Ambassador Mike Mansfield called "the world's most important bilateral relationship" two decades ago. If Mansfield's words are to remain true, or even partly true, today, we need to lift our sights above bickering over bases and put strategy and the world's real problems back at the center of our alliance. 


